crowdsourced_yara_results.description: Detects a suspicious ELF binary with UPX compression
crowdsourced_yara_results.author: Florian Roth (Nextron Systems)

threat_severity.level_description: Severity NONE because the file has no Google antivirus detections and no bad network activity

attributes.magic: ELF 32-bit MSB executable, MIPS, MIPS32 rel2 version 1 (SYSV), statically linked, no section header

crowdsourced_ai_results.analysis: This MIPS32 binary is a dedicated DDoS botnet client, likely a variant of the Gafgyt (Bashlite) or Mirai families, commonly targeting IoT devices. The sample exhibits clear malicious behavior through function sub_4004fc, which establishes communication with a Command and Control (C2) server at 51.79.141.90 and 165.22.255.233. It contains specialized modules for multiple attack vectors, including HTTP floods (sub_401c88), UDP floods, and SSDP amplification attacks (sub_40216c). The binary utilizes system commands like '/bin/busybox ps' and '/bin/busybox kill -9' to manage processes and explicitly targets '/usr/bin/dvrHelper', a common indicator of IoT-focused malware designed to persist on digital video recorders.
